328: Odd Even Linked List
Problem Statement

Given the head of a singly linked list, group all nodes with odd indices together followed by nodes with even indices, and return the reordered list.

Note: The node position is considered (1st, 2nd, 3rd...), not the node value.

Example
Input:  1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5
Output: 1 -> 3 -> 5 -> 2 -> 4
Input:  2 -> 1 -> 3 -> 5 -> 6 -> 4 -> 7
Output: 2 -> 3 -> 6 -> 7 -> 1 -> 5 -> 4
Intuition

Maintain two separate linked lists:

One for nodes at odd positions
One for nodes at even positions

Traverse the list and rearrange pointers such that:

Odd List : 1 -> 3 -> 5
Even List: 2 -> 4

Finally, connect the odd list with the even list.

Approach
Step 1: Handle Edge Cases

If the list is empty or contains only one node, return it directly.

if(head == null || head.next == null){
    return head;
}
Step 2: Initialize Pointers
ListNode odd = head;
ListNode even = odd.next;
ListNode evenHead = even;
odd tracks the current odd-position node.
even tracks the current even-position node.
evenHead stores the head of the even list so it can be attached later.
Step 3: Rearrange Links
while(even != null && even.next != null){
    odd.next = even.next;
    odd = odd.next;

    even.next = even.next.next;
    even = even.next;
}
What happens here?

For:

1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5

Iteration 1:

odd.next = 3
odd = 3

even.next = 4
even = 4

List becomes:

Odd : 1 -> 3 -> 5
Even: 2 -> 4
Step 4: Connect Odd and Even Lists
odd.next = evenHead;

Attach the even list after the odd list.

1 -> 3 -> 5 -> 2 -> 4
Code
class Solution {
    public ListNode oddEvenList(ListNode head) {

        if(head == null || head.next == null){
            return head;
        }

        ListNode odd = head;
        ListNode even = odd.next;
        ListNode evenHead = even;

        while(even != null && even.next != null){

            odd.next = even.next;
            odd = odd.next;

            even.next = even.next.next;
            even = even.next;
        }

        odd.next = evenHead;

        return head;
    }
}
Dry Run
Input
1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5
Initial State
odd = 1
even = 2
evenHead = 2
Iteration 1
odd.next = 3
odd = 3

even.next = 4
even = 4

Current Structure:

Odd : 1 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5
Even: 2 -> 4 -> 5
Iteration 2
odd.next = 5
odd = 5

even.next = null
even = null

Current Structure:

Odd : 1 -> 3 -> 5
Even: 2 -> 4
Final Step
odd.next = evenHead;

Result:

1 -> 3 -> 5 -> 2 -> 4
Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity
O(n)

Each node is visited exactly once.

Space Complexity
O(1)

Only a few pointers are used.

Key Concepts Learned
Multiple Pointer Manipulation
odd.next = even.next;
even.next = even.next.next;

Used to separate odd and even indexed nodes.

Storing a Reference
ListNode evenHead = even;

Important because the even list needs to be attached back after processing.

Takeaway

The idea is to maintain two chains:

Odd Indexed Nodes
1 -> 3 -> 5

Even Indexed Nodes
2 -> 4

After traversal, connect:

Odd List + Even List

Result:

1 -> 3 -> 5 -> 2 -> 4

This achieves the optimal solution with:

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)
Pattern Learned

Linked List Rewiring / Pointer Manipulation – a common pattern used in many linked list interview problems.
